The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-play area on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design staff since last year.
Arch.Design, the design and architecture firm from whose studios a whole series of renowned Brno buildings originate, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is interested in the project managers returning to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the opportunity to work shorter, Kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
The civil engineers have so much easier to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and, with the support of management, they were able to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company's mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (subsidies of CZK 2.8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and qualified personnel and operations were provided for a period of 2 years.
After 2 years of funding, Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the Minikindergarten for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating actively assisting in the implementation of the application.
The children are cared for by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day changes over several children.
The kindergarten is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting programme of pre-school education.
Not only do the children play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, while also learning English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to children.
What more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus the stress is eliminated when the children are picked up late from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn up fish mouths.
This is Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knobenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the scales-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only when you take a closer look that you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole façade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and entwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-like shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and strips.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló apartment house alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on its drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner arose and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in Park Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "Knobenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gawning house".
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, the patron of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, which was unique at the time, with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
It's a bit bizarre, her 45-degree inclination already seems.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at the time and did not let himself be deceived by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the relevant building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded remedy two years later when it was completed.
Among other things, the councillors also stumbled upon the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the city's request to do so, Josep Batlló submitted an application for the permit to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
By the basic elements of the conversion all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked on a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably, without having to renounce a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, the house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is disguised and the courtyards is impressive.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply used the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by everyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, yes, they were extended to other common rooms and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard handle, it amounts to 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the housemates and visit him at home.
