The first step towards making seems quite simple.
Luciano dumps the basic ingredients milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large blender that heats everything to 85 degrees using an electronic program and then immediately cools to four degrees.
Then he turns a cock on the machine, and out comes a pasteurized white base cream, basis for all types of milk ice cream.
The lecturer is immediately besieged with questions: Can ice cream only be produced with natural substances without stabilizer?
How can one let one's own desire for experimentation run free?
Luciano warns against being misled by the zeitgeist.
Those who talk about ice cream "only from natural ingredients" may still have used stabilizers - usually a natural product, such as guar gum from the guar bean.
Of course, you can also make ice cream without a stabilizer, only then it has to be sold within one day, otherwise it sags in itself, and the customer bites on loud ice grains.
Certain variations on the base mass are allowed.
It becomes more exciting with the aromas.
