Now the students are allowed to use the ice machines.
Luciano makes them produce four different types of vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut ice cream - with or without eggs in the basic mass, with more or less vanilla flavour or other natural additives.
The fruit ice varieties are also subjected to the same experiment.
More flavors, more fruit puree - this is not necessarily better in terms of taste.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily taste nutty if it contains more hazelnuts.
The most popular kiwi ice cream manufactures the working group that uses more fruits, less water and slightly less stabilizer.
Only a balanced mixture really enhances the taste of a gelato, says Luciano.
Ice production is a calculation task: if peach puree is used with a lot of sugar, the sugar content in the basic recipe must be reduced.
Lemon ice cream requires an extra portion of sugar.
Luciano draws out a device by which he determines the sugar content of the fruit varieties (wincers measure the oechsle in the grape must).
Fortunately, tables make computing easier.
Making ice no longer requires as much physical effort as before.
Not only the device for the automatic production of the base mass helps.
There is also a device in which the finished ice mixture is whipped creamy at the same time and cooled to minus temperatures.
Despite all automation, small breakdowns do not remain.
