A sloppy election
No one expected that the elections in Haiti on 28 November would be perfect.
But the facts far surpassed the fears of the election workers who hurried to help the thrashed country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes cast, ballot tickets in the Rinnstein, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were only part of the problems.
Voters opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless by the earthquake in January, roamed around in search of an option.
Some eventually gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected leaders, demanded that the election results be lifted due to an alleged fraud.
There were some violent protests throughout the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election "as quite good in many matters".
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
