On the other hand, José Antonio Olavarrieta, Director General of the Spanish Savings Banks Association (CECA), said that this second round would not take place.
"I believe that most of the mergers have been completed, and the inclusion of Cajasol in the Banca Cívica group cannot be regarded as a second round, but rather as adjustments."
"Most of it has been completed. It may be that we have thirteen or fourteen instead of seven, but all important processes have already been completed. They have been controlled by Banco de España, who has strongly supported all processes."
At a breakfast organized by the Association of Managing Directors and Managers of Aragon (ADEA), Olavarrieta stated that the concentration process "was completed as soon as possible and that we must be satisfied with the timely process that was established in earlier times, not now, as part of the business plans with Banco de España," he stressed.
"The transition from 45 savings banks with an average of 28 000 million assets to 17 with 75 500 million each is a historically incomparable process. The number of financial institutions has been reduced by 62 percent and they are now much larger, with which we have fulfilled the Basel Agreement," he emphasized.
Olavarrieta stated that "there are a number of inappropriate opinions about the slowness of the process, the unseriousness and nonsense" because "Banco de España exhorts us to conclude on time before the end of the year."
The Director General of CECA, José Antonio Olavarrieta, yesterday assured that Spain had one of the most rigorous financing systems in Europe and "perhaps" the whole world and added that those who doubted this would do so "without deeper knowledge".
The manager noted that in the current economic environment, we need to "not worry" about the situation of financial institutions and savings banks, which have undergone a "very important" concentration process that will be carried out "as soon as possible".
He also recalled that the Spanish banks had passed the ECB’s stress tests in July very well.
Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has chosen to retain the euro, but at the same time has established conditions for the whole of the European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adaptation measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment companies or the lifting of the EUR 426 support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, Deputy Head of Government Elena Salgado supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is taking on a fundamentally new perspective for shaping our future, which collides with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second is the reintroduction of the German mark - although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a transformation of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macro-economic control; strict financial management; punishment of the countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the suspension of payments by some countries as well as the extension of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. That is why there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government withdrew a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of the drift between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country when Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to rescue Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the public opinion were absolutely against saving Greece.
Finally, Merkel comes out again in the last days of October with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable the rescue of a country and at the same time for private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it spurred the Irish crisis and all of the following.
But their proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be taking part in the reform of the European Union, which will allow for these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures must be taken now - the old functioning of the euro will no longer be possible from this date on.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the opposing countries will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and in this case the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard course in growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not understand.
It is not just a matter of reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will move into more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero has understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the large companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like it would change anything.
Among the options envisaged is the fact that we would have to leave the euro area full of less serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sport and regular circulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The exclusion, allegedly initiated by two players of the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the game of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League, led to a lot of ink being shed about whether or not it was an unsports act and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed penalty in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the debate about the case presented is that a team from the Real Madrid football club (who in his anthem pretended nobleness and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role in this, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not explicitly prohibited by the Statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute a rule-making process. Indeed, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sporting spirit should be investigated.
The sport spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players gain an unjustified benefit from the counter team. This did not happen either.
The paradox of the Real Madrid players' action is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by misappropriation or circumvention of rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but should be as conspicuous as possible for it to be punished by the referee.
The players waited and accepted the penalty joyfully.
Another question is what kind of benefit the offenders drew from the deliberate fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was not placed in a less favorable position nor was there any advantage for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also withdraw. Moreover, with this approach, the players receive a sanction and pass into the second card cycle, in which they exit with a card less than in the first cycle due to a pile of cards.
This does not make it so clear whether it really is an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not against the sport spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to maximise the benefits of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (this would actually be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), they rather wanted to choose when they would submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing from a punishment.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the regulatory environment has been blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemics arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the kind of provoked rule transfer.
The damage done by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than aesthetic.
Offer campaign to catch customers for group Christmas dinners in Barcelona
The dictatorship of the calendar this year drops an avalanche of reservations to the days 16 and 17 December.
The celebrations paid by employees themselves spread out. They don’t want to spend more than 20 to 30 euros.
Like the Turrón and the Christmas lottery, there are also group dinners in the pre-Christmas period, which supply the catering and leisure industry of Barcelona with oxygen. However, as a result of the economic crisis, they trigger a price offensive in order to capture the customer segment, which represents the great mass: Almost everyone wants to spend between 20 and 30 euros for a lunch or dinner, the surveyed entrepreneurs and associations confirm.
To make accounting a bit more complicated, the calendar (Silverster falls on a Friday) dropped all orders into the week of December 13, with the result of an avalanche of dinner reservations on two top days (the 16th and 17th) and almost no orders the week before.
Since 2008, when the bad times began, many companies have stopped group dinners for household reasons.
In order not to give up this tradition, many workers pay for it from their own pockets.
Whatever the economic situation, the lowest prices are required, confirmed Gaietà Farràs, President of the Barcelona Board of Restaurants.
The representative of the umbrella organisation does not dare to predict what the holidays will look like this month.
"People think about it 'tirely before they reserve."
"They want to go out, but they pay great attention to prices," he stresses.
The business will go well with those who "offer quality at good prices with good service", he adds, and reminds us that customers save in times of crisis, which is why prices of 25 euros are the most in demand.
In a survey in various centrally located restaurants, it turns out that the evening of 17 December leads the providers to collapse.
The Soteras Group says that the demand for this Friday with the intention of spending less than 30 euros would be booming. The Group has adapted its menus with complete offers of between 25 and 35 euros to the economic situation.
With another leading group, Andilana, which has 16 restaurants in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), the peculiarity of the calendar has led to early reservations, even from the beginning of November.
"We have made the impossible possible to maintain the previous year's prices with menus for every taste from 19.95 to 30 euros," he explains.
With AN Grup, which leads El Mussol, Attic, QuQu and a total of 23 locals, one does not lose the optimism after the second quarter the revenues bloom again and good, although concentrated on a few days, prospects for the Christmas business are expected.
Sources from the Group point out that the 18th will also be an overactive day with groups of friends celebrating Christmas.
In addition to the six group menus, a Christmas menu for 30 euros or more has been added as a price hit. One has the impression that the customers are willing to spend 10 percent more than in the previous year and in return want more details, such as Cava.
Some companies also see green sprouts sprouting, which is why the employees are invited again. This gives the impression that the group dinners are back in the upswing.
On the part of the Fecasarm umbrella association (with associations such as the Bar, Restaurant and Leisure Association of Barcelona), the vice president, Enric Gomà, trusts to see the end of the tunnel and notes that the reservations are quite "lively" overall, although the customers "beat out a maximum".
However, the fun of celebrating had not declined, no matter who pays.
Pakistan’s nuclear programme is causing great concern in the US
Islamabad makes nuclear weapons "faster than any other country".
Wikileak revelations confirm Taliban-Pakistan relations.
The content of the correspondence between the North American Embassy in Pakistan and the US Department of State revealed by the Wikileaks Internet portal confirms the enormous concerns of the Pakistan nuclear program Washington.
On the edge of the clarifying and succulent details provided by the documents on the content of the talks and the thinking of accredited North American diplomats in Islamabad, they reveal that cooperation between the two countries is not reinforced in terms of nuclear security, but rather is "abolished" on the contrary, and that the unstable Asian country is producing more nuclear weapons "to a faster rhytmus than any other country".
In particular, the peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled, but their parts are stored to make their destruction more difficult in the event of a possible attack - make Washington sleepless nights.
The following risks are listed by the Ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, in a report before the visit of the former head of the National Security Council, James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the Taliban-attacked area, the probable dispersion of nuclear material and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear material".
The large number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is no longer seen by the US alone, but also by Russia as an outburst and reason to exercise caution.
"Pakistan must hire strict religious personnel to guard nuclear installations; due to the low level of education and culture, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people working on nuclear or missile programs," said expert Yuri Korolev from the Russian Foreign Ministry in a meeting with his North American counterparts.
New to the documentation revealed by Julian Assange's Internet portal is that the cooperation between the US and Pakistan in terms of nuclear proliferation is slowing down and the increased pace in which Pakistan produces nuclear weapons.
In May, an embassy office that describes communication with Pakistan as "frustrating" explains: "There is often no transparency; we do not receive any answers to help, or they are rejected."
In another statement, Peter Lavoy, official of the State Intelligence Service for South Asia, confirms that "despite the economic catastrophe Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons as fast as no other country."
Ambassador Patterson asks Washington to "clarify" the person responsible during a visit by General Ashfaq Kayani, Chief of the Army, that "Pakistan's army must cease its tacit support of terrorist groups."
On the hunt for Wikileak's boss
Obama appoints a high person responsible for the anti-terrorism struggle to prevent new revelations.
Interpol issued a red warning to persecute and find Assange.
Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Jullian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth in which the facts can be solved only difficult.
Yesterday Interpol issued a "red warning" for the "finding and persecution" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional order of arrest.
Besides, it's not new, it's from November 20th.
It also has nothing to do with the recent disclosure of over four million diplomatic documents from the United States, but with the accusations of sexual abuse that the Australian must face in Sweden.
Furthermore, the lawyer of the founder of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, "the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange."
Already on the 20th, the international police authority based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but it was not announced until yesterday after receiving the authority from the Swedish authorities.
The 188 Interpol countries are required to identify and locate Assange, "in order to arrest and deliver him for the time being."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red warning, many member states, according to the organization, regard the red warning as a licence for arrest - which must be carried out by the national police - in particular if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is probably present.
The action outraged Assange's lawyers, who issued a letter informing them that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks is willing to answer the questions of the Swedish authorities via video conference.
They also recall that Assange requested to leave Sweden and was compared with the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's head of security, by the prosecutor.
"This is like a hunt, not like a legal persecution," the letter accuses.
While the world is looking for him - and his mother from Australia affirms the innocence of her son - Assange stays in an unknown place, but not silent.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the head of Time magazine via Skype from an indefinite location. During the interview, he applied for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN and thus violate international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign," he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by the press secretary of the White House, Robert Gibbs, who described the request for resignation as "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not sure why we should value the opinion of a guy with a website," he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a high-ranking figure in charge of the anti-terrorism struggle, Rusell Travers, with preventing new document disclosures.
The attempt by President Barack Obama’s spokesman to pay less attention to Assange contrasts with the opinions that conservative politicians and commentators have expressed these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the National Security Committee of the House of Representatives from January onwards, has called on the Department of State to investigate the possibility of putting Wikileaks on the list of terrorist organizations "to seize their funds and prosecute anyone who supports them or makes a contribution."
Tom Flanagan, advisor to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone even further, and he had to revoke his statement that Assange had to be "murdered."
"Obama would have to turn him into a target and use an unmanned plane or something."
Those who did not apologize were Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and possible presidential candidate.
"Whoever it was who leaked information in the government, he is guilty of treason, and all that is not execution is too mild a punishment," he told Fox.
Puigcercós seeks peace in the ERC with a wink to the Carod
The Republican leader allows the party to hold a secret vote on its continued existence in office.
Huguet proposes a more pluralistic government and the end of the general assembly principle.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe to avoid for the tens of years an internal turmoil in the ranks of the ERC without direction after the loss of 11 MPs and half of the votes.
The party leader is aware that his threat of resignation is not enough for former party leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira, but he also knows that today the influence of this sector is as weakened as its mentor himself and will not cause him the same headache as other former currents.
Therefore, the leader of Esquerra tries to win the new critics with a wink, which would secure his position until the next municipal elections.
For the beginning, it was announced yesterday that the more than 200 Regional Council members of ERC could speak out in secret about his stay in office.
With ballots, not with a high hand.
If the carodists wanted to give the president a parking ticket, they could do so without fearing reprisals.
In fact, the boss wants to avoid both the impression of division and submission to his person.
In several interviews he affirmed that he would feel unconfirmed with half of the votes plus one, and he added without stating percentages that a result "in Bulgarian style" would not be good either.
The Carod allies are demanding more from the president than just providing the party with its office, an inadequate gesture, as Puigcercós controls the supreme body of Congresses.
But since they do not have a sufficient majority to encourage resignations, they will agree with the board on a plan of action from now until May.
To this end, they expect to be able to participate in the preparation of the document on strategic reorientation, which will be submitted to the Council for vote on the 18th.
Their intention is to vouch for Puigcercós. In return, he is to promise to move the congress forward to the autumn of 2011, which the party leader already thinks is a fact.
The party chairman of the ERC believes the "polyphony" is a pity of stability and he strives once and for all to enable the organization to wash its dirty laundry behind closed doors.
In this sense, the article signed by incumbent Conseller Josep Huguet in his blog is symptomatic.
In view of the fact that Puigcercós is an ideologist, the owner of Innovació considered it to be a fact that the party president was supported "in exchange for various goals".
He counted five, two of which are in the foreground.
First, the "restructuring" of the Executive Board, so that it represents at least 90 percent of the party members, that is, the inclusion of new faces from Carod's environment.
The second could be the big news.
Huguet suggests that ERC should finally abandon the general assembly principle as a way of functioning.
In doing so, he advocates a reform of the Statutes, which should enable congresses to be held with elected delegates.
Puigcercós's team, who fought for it at the last two congresses, is obsessed with the end of the general assembly model - an exception to the Spanish party system.
In fact, at the quake assembly in 2008, the party leadership was charged with reviewing the general assembly principle at a congress that was to deal with reforming the statutes.
This date is still pending, since infogle's internal rest of the last few years was not advisable to tackle this matter.
Now, without the critical sectors lying in wait, the time may have come to take up this matter again and to conclude it forever.
