China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
At COP16, China’s representative said that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and that it would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China holds its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16, assures.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and convert its industry.
He said that over the last four years his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its objectives, but would work on this matter with the international community.
He explained that the Chinese climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress had been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which included the objectives of reducing emissions of gases, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the federal authorities had worked with the central government and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he said, several multi-year plans have already been launched or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those receiving funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Effective Use Programme, which has been introduced over the past five years and has received United Nations (UN) investment, government and private hands.
There is also a provincial climate change project, another on the exchange of traditional light bulbs through energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he said.
Martin Krol, scientific government advisor on climate change in this country, confirmed that China’s efforts were far greater than was generally believed to be.
He pointed out that per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amounted to six tonnes per person, while in the United States they amount to 100 tonnes. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to pollution.
It also makes unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has been increased by twenty percent over the last five years and another is expected to happen by 2020, he said.
Legal exclusion Espinos: César Nava
The national leader of the PAN stated that the former president of the party had the right to appeal to the National Order Commission and to demand what the law would grant him.
The national leader of the PAN, César Nava Vázquez, assured that the exclusion of Manuel Espino Barriento was right and that the former party chairman of the PAN had the right to appeal to the National Order Commission and to demand what the right was to him.
In an interview with Gabino Cué Monteagudos as governor of the state prior to the appeal, he stated that the exclusion of Espino was a decision taken at local level.
"It is an independent decision of the Order Commission in Sonora."
"Mr Espino has the right in his case to appeal to the Comisión de Orden del Consejo Nacional for a decision to be taken by a competent body," he added.
On the other hand, he said that it was not time to think about 2012 and that an alliance with the presidential candidate had never sat at the negotiating table.
Nava Vázquez was convinced that Acción Nacional would emerge stronger from the internal vote on 4 and 5 December, in which his successor will be elected.
"This (an alliance in 2012) is a topic that has never been on the negotiating table, at least not until now. It was a proposal for the municipal election, it was successful and fulfilled its purpose," he said.
The Panist leader explained that the PAN looks back on 71 years of dialogue, so "internal competition does not frighten us; on the contrary, "we enjoy it and it strengthens us," he commented.
He said that the Council would no doubt choose the or the best chairman Acción Nacional needs for the next three years, so he would transfer the stakes "to the one that the Council would determine."
"I am unconcerned and open. I would be proud to give each of the five the office of party chairman."
He predicted that the party's recovery in the last elections of July 4 would be reflected in the next elections, although "it is not time to think about 2012."
"Now it's about assisting Governor Gabino Cué in his task."
In this context, he stressed that the three governments that emerged from alliances between Oaxaca, Puebla and Sinaloa would carry the flag and be observed throughout the country. Therefore, "many hopes and longings are placed in them and I am sure that Gabino is at the height of the demands."
When asked about the PRI's criticism of President Felipe Calderón about his discourse course in his four-year government, César Nava called on the PRI's supporters to reflect on the six-year period of former Presidents Ernesto Zedillo and Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
"If the PRI believes that the governments of Zedillo and Salinas were better than those of Fox and Calderón, they should begin to defend them, should they finally get out of the closet," he affirmed.
He is of the opinion that the owner of the federal government would be able to make expressions such as those he could make in his discourse in the Auditorio Nacional, because in this country there would be no ban on the mouth and even less censorship.
Obama advocates the law in Twitter for undocumented students
"If you are in favour of passing the Dream Act, call your senators and urge them to pass this law," the President of the United States tweeted on the popular social network.
President Barack Obama today supported the nationwide mobilization to support the Dream Act - Law on Legalization of Undocumented Students with a message on his personal blog on the social network Twitter.
"If you are in favour of passing the Dream Act, call your senators and urge them to pass this law," Obama tweeted.
His brief statement contains a cyberlink to a broader document that calls on the public to get in touch with their senators, as the vote of the law is imminent.
"With your voice that we are waiting for, the time has come to listen to you," he emphasizes.
The news was spread after the 42 Republican senators threatened to block all votes for each law, except the extension of tax reductions from the Bush era and the government's funding would be extended.
