And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and therefore they have to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide a point of acceptance.
According to the report, however, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to generate electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars a year on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
